Bring a large #saucepan{} of water to the boil with @salt{1/2%tsp} for the noodles.

When boiling, add the @egg noodle nests{2} to the water and cook until tender, ~{4%minutes}.

Once cooked, drain in a #sieve{} and run under cold water to stop them sticking together.

Meanwhile, trim the @pak choi{1}(trimmed), then thinly slice widthways.

Peel and grate the @garlic cloves{2} (or use a #garlic press{}). Cut the @lime{1} into wedges.

Trim and peel the @carrot{1}. Use the #peeler{} to peel long ribbons down the length of the carrot, stopping at the core.

Drain the @king prawns{300%g}.

> IMPORTANT: Wash your hands and equipment after handling raw prawns.

Heat a drizzle of @oil{} in a large #frying pan{} on medium-high heat.

Once hot, add the garlic and stir-fry until fragrant, ~{30%seconds}.

Stir the @bulgogi sauce{150%g} and @water{50%ml} for the sauce into the garlic, then bring to the boil.

Stir in the prawns and cook for another ~{3-4%minutes}.

Next, add the carrot ribbons and pak choi to the pan. Simmer until the prawns are cooked through and the veg is tender, ~{2-3%minutes}.

> IMPORTANT: The prawns are cooked when pink on the outside and opaque in the middle.

Once the prawns are cooked, add the noodles and a squeeze of lime juice to the sauce.

Toss to coat the noodles in the sauce, stirring frequently until everything is piping hot, ~{1-2%minutes}.

Taste and add more salt, @?ground black pepper{}, or lime juice if needed. Add a splash of @?water{} if you feel it needs it.

Share the bulgogi prawn noodles between your #bowls{}.

Serve any remaining lime wedges alongside for squeezing over.

Enjoy!